{"title_page": "Vincenzo Di Nicola", "text_new": "[[File:Vincenzo Di Nicola APA Photo Nov 2017b.jpg|thumb|Prof. Vincenzo Di Nicola, MPhil, MD, PhD, FRCPC, DFAPA]]\n'''Vincenzo Di Nicola''' is an [[Italian Canadians|Italian-Canadian]] [[psychologist]], [[psychiatrist]] and [[family therapist]], and [[Philosophy of mind|philosopher of mind]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwumc.edu/smhs/facultydirectory/profile.cfm?empName=Vincenzo%20Di%20Nicola&FacID=2066720133#|title=Faculty Directory {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences {{!}} The George Washington University|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=www.gwumc.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> \n\nDi Nicola is a tenured Professor in the Dept. of Psychiatry & Addictions at the [[University of Montreal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etudes.umontreal.ca/publications/annu_pdf/2011-2012/1erCycle/MED_tap.pdf|title=Faculte de Medicine|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2011\u20132012|website=|publisher=University of Montreal|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> where he founded and directs the postgraduate course on Psychiatry and the Humanities,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/03/23/psychiatry-and-the-humanities-postgraduate-course-in-the-faculty-of-medicine-university-of-montreal/|title=Psychiatry and the Humanities: Postgraduate Course in the Faculty of Medicine, University of Montreal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2017-03-23|website=Blog of the APA|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> and Clinical Professor in the Dept. of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at [[The George Washington University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwumc.edu/smhs/facultydirectory/profile.cfm?empName=Vincenzo%20Di%20Nicola&FacID=2066720133#|title=Faculty Directory {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences {{!}} The George Washington University|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=www.gwumc.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> where he gave The 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smhs.gwu.edu/psychiatry/events/grand-rounds-4th-annual-stokes-endowment-lecture|title=Grand Rounds: The 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture {{!}} The Department of Psychiatry & Behavioral Sciences|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=smhs.gwu.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> In 2001, Di Nicola was made Professor, Honoris Causa of [[:pt:Faculdades_Integradas_do_Oeste_de_Minas|Faculdades Integradas do Oeste de Minas (FADOM)]] in Minas Gerais, Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://recherche.umontreal.ca/english/our-researchers/professors-directory/researcher/is/in17672/|title=Researcher|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=La recherche - Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>   \n\nDi Nicola was the recipient of the Camille Laurin Prize from the F\u00e9d\u00e9ration des m\u00e9decins sp\u00e9cialistes du Qu\u00e9bec.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration des m\u00e9decins sp\u00e9cialistes du Qu\u00e9bec |date=June 4, 2011 |url=http://www.fmsq.org/en/nouvelle/-/journal_content/contentdisplayerportlet_WAR_contentdisplayer10/10275/52216;jsessionid=8AA0EFBC8F03956910634FBD9C2DF83F?p_p_state=pop_up&_contentdisplayerportlet_WAR_contentdisplayer10_viewMode=print |title=AMPQ Annual Prizes |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> He was made a Fellow of the [[American Psychiatric Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psych.org/MainMenu/EducationCareerDevelopment/Meetings/Past-APA-Meetings/2011-Annual-Meeting/Virtual-Registration-Bag_1/Onsite-Meeting-Guides/Convocation-Program.aspx?FT=.pdf|title=55th convocation of distinguished fellows|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=May 16, 2011|website=|publisher=The American Psychiatric Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 2, 2012}}</ref> (APA) in 2011 and Distinguished Fellow of the APA in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://recherche.umontreal.ca/english/our-researchers/professors-directory/researcher/is/in17672/|title=Researcher, Dept of Psychiatry|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=La recherche - Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> In 2018, the [[American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry]] (AACAP) awarded Di Nicola the AACAP Jeanne Spurlock, MD, Lecture and Award on Diversity and Culture<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aacap.org/App_Themes/AACAP/docs/awards/aacap_honors_book_2018.pdf|title=AACAP Honors 2018|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=25 October 2018|website=www.aacap.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> for which he gave the lecture, \u201cBorders and Belonging, Culture and Community: From Adversity to Diversity in Transcultural Child and Family Psychiatry.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2018-10-01|title=Borders and Belonging, Culture and Community: From Adversity to Diversity in Transcultural Child and Family Psychiatry|url=https://www.jaacap.org/article/S0890-8567(18)31360-1/abstract|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry|language=English|volume=57|issue=10|pages=S116|doi=10.1016/j.jaac.2018.09.013|issn=0890-8567|via=}}</ref>  \n\nDi Nicola is a collaborating partner of the Collaborating Centre for Values-based Practice in Health and Social Care at St. Catherine's College, Oxford University<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://valuesbasedpractice.org/who-are-we-2/list-of-project-partners/list-of-individuals/professor-vincenzo-di-nicola/|title=Professor Vincenzo Di Nicola|date=2019-11-08|website=The Collaborating Centre for Values-based practice in Health and Social Care|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> where he participated in the Advanced Studies Seminar dedicated to his work on cultural aspects of eating disorders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://valuesbasedpractice.org/anorexia-multiforme-revisited/|title=Anorexia Multiforme Revisited|date=2019-10-15|website=The Collaborating Centre for Values-based practice in Health and Social Care|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> In 2019, he founded and was elected President of the Canadian Association of Social Psychiatry<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/associations/|title=ASSOCIATIONS {{!}} WASP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> and was made an Honorary Fellow of the [https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/ World Association of Social Psychiatry],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/wasp-honorary-fellows/|title=WASP Honorary Fellows {{!}} WASP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> of which he is President-Elect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/wasp-executive-committee/|title=WASP Executive Committee {{!}} WASP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nDi Nicola is the author of two books, ''[[A Stranger in the Family]]: Culture, Families, and Therapy'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwnorton.com/books/9780393702286|title=A Stranger in the Family: Culture, Families, and Therapy|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=wwnorton.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> integrating family therapy and cultural psychiatry to create cultural family therapy, and ''Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atropospress.com/letters-to-a-young-therapist-relational-practices-for-the-coming-community|title=Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Atropos Press|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> an overview of principles of relational psychology and therapy.\n\n==Education==\nDi Nicola trained in psychology, medicine and psychiatry, and in philosophy: with a BA (First Class Honours) in Psychology from [[McGill University]] (1976), MPhil in Clinical Psychology, [[Institute of Psychiatry, Psychology and Neuroscience|Institute of Psychiatry]], University of London (1978), [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] from [[McMaster University]] (1981), Diploma in Psychiatry from McGill University (1986), and later in his career, with a PhD (Summa Cum Laude) in Philosophy from the [[European Graduate School|European Graduate Schoo]]<nowiki/>l (2012).<ref name=Alumnotes>{{cite web |publisher=McGill University, McGill News, Alumni magazine |date=Spring\u2013Summer 2011 |url=http://publications.mcgill.ca/mcgillnews/2011/06/02/alumnotes-springsummer-2011/ |title=Alumnotes Spring/Summer2011 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611112929/http://publications.mcgill.ca/mcgillnews/2011/06/02/alumnotes-springsummer-2011/ |archive-date=June 11, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Mactimes>{{cite web |publisher=McMaster University |date=Spring 2011 |url=http://issuu.com/mactimes/docs/times_april_2011_-_updated |title=Mactimes/Spring2011 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwumc.edu/smhs/facultydirectory/profile.cfm?empName=Vincenzo%20Di%20Nicola&FacID=2066720133|title=Faculty Directory {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences {{!}} The George Washington University|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=www.gwumc.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nDi Nicola's career has shown several foci, examining children, families and culture in various combinations.<ref name=\"Doi\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/136346158502200201 |title=Family Therapy and Transcultural Psychiatry: An Emerging Synthesis Part I: The Conceptual Basis |year=1985 |last1=DiNicola |first1=V. F. |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |volume=22 |issue=2 |page=81}}</ref><ref name=\"Isbn\">{{cite book |title=A stranger in the family: culture, families and therapy |first=Vincenzo F |last=DiNicola |location=New York ; London |publisher=W.W. Norton |date=1997 |isbn=978-0-39370-228-6}}</ref><ref name=\"InOkpaku\">{{Cite book |editor-last=Okpaku |editor-first=Sanuel O. |title=Clinical Methods in Transcultural Psychiatry |journal=Cultural Diversity & Ethnic Minority Psychology |volume=8 |issue=3 |year=1998 |place=Washington, DC |publisher=American Psychiatric Association |pages=365\u2013390 |doi=10.1037/1099-9809.8.3.298 |isbn=978-0-88048-710-8}}</ref>\n\n==== '''Cultural Family Therapy''' ====\n''Main article:'' [[A Stranger in the Family|''A Stranger in the Family'']]\n\nHis approach to working with families across cultures brought together a new synthesis of family therapy and transcultural psychiatry.<ref name=\"Doi\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=DiNicola|first=Vincenzo F.|date=1985|title=Family Therapy and Transcultural Psychiatry: An Emerging Synthesis|journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review|language=en-US|volume=22|issue=3|pages=151\u2013180|doi=10.1177/136346158502200301|issn=0041-1108}}</ref> Critical reviews were positive and encouraging by leaders in family therapy, such as [[Mara Selvini Palazzoli]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Selvini Palazzoli|first=Mara|date=1986|title=COMMENTS ON DI NICOLA'S \"FAMILY THERAPY AND TRANSCULTURAL PSYCHIATRY: PARTS 1 AND 2 (Published in T.P.R.R. Volume XXII, Nos. 2 and 3, pp. 81-113 and 151-180). LETTER FROM MARA SELVINI PALAZZOLI, M.D., Nuovo Centro Per Lo Studio Della Famiglia, Viale Vitorio Veneto, 12, Milano 21124, Italy|journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review|language=en|volume=23|issue=1|pages=83\u201385|doi=10.1177/136346158602300114}}</ref> and Celia Jaes Falicov,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/sage/comments-on-di-nicola-s-family-therapy-and-transcultural-psychiatry-QTrL8CpL6c |title=Comments on DI NICOLA'S Family Therapy and Transcultural Psychiatry: Parts 1 and 2 (TPRR, XXII, Nos. 2 and 3, pp. 81-113 and 151-180) |author=Celia Jaes Falicov |journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review |volume=23 |issue=2 |page=5 |date=Jun 1, 1986 |via=DeepDyve |accessdate=2013-02-23}}</ref> as well as those in transcultural psychiatry, such as [[Armando Favazza]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Favazza|first=Armando R.|date=1 March 1986|title=LETTER FROM ARMANDO R. FAVAZZA, M.D., Section of General Psychiatry, Department of Psychiatry, School of Medicine, Uni versity of Missouri-Columbia, Three Hospital Drive, Columbia, Missouri 65201, U.S.A|journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review|language=en-US|volume=23|issue=1|pages=86\u201391|doi=10.1177/136346158602300115|issn=0041-1108}}</ref> When his work was collected into his model of cultural family therapy in ''[[A Stranger in the Family]]''<ref name=\"Isbn\" /> in 1997, it was received as an important contribution to working with immigrant families.<ref>{{cite journal |volume=187 |pages=453\u2013454 |journal=Journal of Nervous & Mental Disease |date=July 1999 |title=A Stranger in The Family: Culture, Families, and Therapy |author=Comas-D\u00edaz, Lillian |issue=7 |doi=10.1097/00005053-199907000-00016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Krause, Inga-Britt|date=Dec 1, 1998|title=Book Reviews : A STRANGER IN THE FAMILY. CULTURE, FAMILIES AND THERAPY Vincenzo Di Nicola: W.W. Norton & Co. New York, 1997. Pp. 380, Hb. Bibl; index 33.00. ISBN 0-393-70228-6|url=http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/sage/book-reviews-a-stranger-in-the-family-culture-families-and-therapy-T9ipODhRDl|journal=International Journal of Social Psychiatry|volume=44|issue=4|page=312|doi=10.1177/002076409804400409|accessdate=2012-04-09|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |volume=20 |page=174 |journal=Australian and New Zealand Journal of Family Therapy |year=1999 |url=http://www.anzjft.com/pages/articles/1103.pdf |author=Sexton, Leo |title=REVIEWS: Independent comment on audio-visual and print materials |accessdate=2012-04-09 |issue=3 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318061824/http://www.anzjft.com/pages/articles/1103.pdf |archive-date=2012-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bezonsky-Jacobs|first=Rhona|date=1999|title=Review of 'A Stranger in the Family: Culture, Families, and Therapy'|journal=PRISME|volume=No. 30|pages=156\u2013158|isbn=0393702286}}</ref> A Brazilian edition in Portuguese translation appeared in 1998.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|title=Um Estranho na Fam\u00edlia: Cultura, Fam\u00edlias e Terapia|date=1998|publisher=Artmed|year=1998|isbn=85-7307-464-7|location=Porto Alegre|pages=|oclc=69926813}}</ref> Di Nicola continued to elaborate his model of cultural family therapy in articles, chapters,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibs.it/famiglie-immigrate-psicoterapia-transculturale-libro-vari/e/9788846456397|title=Famiglie sulla soglia. Citt\u00e0 invisibili, identit\u00e0 invisibili. In: Famiglie immigrate e psicoterapia transculturale|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2012|year=2012|editor-last=Andolfi|editor-first=Maurizio|website=www.ibs.it|publisher=FrancoAngeli|pages=34-57|language=Italian|trans-title=Families on the threshold: Invisible cities, invisible identities. In: Immigrant Families and Transcultural Psychotherapy|publication-place=Milan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a follow-up volume, ''Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/703204731|title=Letters to a Young Therapist Relational Practices for the Coming Community|date=2011|publisher=Atropos Books|others=|year=2011|isbn=978-0-9831734-5-8|location=New York and Dresden|pages=|oclc=703204731}}</ref> as well as invitations to present the 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture in family studies at [[George Washington University|The George Washington University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smhs.gwu.edu/psychiatry/events/grand-rounds-4th-annual-stokes-endowment-lecture|title=Grand Rounds: The 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture {{!}} The Department of Psychiatry & Behavioral Sciences|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=April 25, 2013|website=smhs.gwu.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and a thirty-year perspective on his model presented at [[McGill University]] where he first developed it <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/psychiatry/channels/event/grand-rounds-threshold-event-thirty-years-cultural-family-therapy-dr-vincenzo-di-nicola-259678|title=Grand Rounds: From the Threshold to the Event: Thirty Years of Cultural Family Therapy - Dr. Vincenzo Di Nicola|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=March 18, 2016|website=Department of Psychiatry, McGill University|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and the Accademia di Psicoterapia della [http://www.accademiapsico.it/ Famiglia] in Rome, Italy where Di Nicola's model is taught.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slideshare.net/PhiloShrink/dalla-soglia-allevento-lo-svolgimento-della-terapia-familiare-culturale|title=Dalla Soglia all'Evento: Lo Svolgimento della Terapia Familiare Culturale. Giornata di Lezioni Teoriche - Accademia di Psicoterapia della Famiglia, Roma, Italia|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=April 9, 2016|website=www.slideshare.net/PhiloShrink|language=Italian|trans-title=From the Threshold to the Event: The Development of Cultural Family Therapy. Academic Teaching Day - Academy of Family Psychotherapy, Rome, Italy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== '''Social and Cultural Psychiatry''' ====\nAnother integration was in bringing together child psychiatry with transcultural research to call for the new field of transcultural child psychiatry.<ref name=\"InOkpaku\" /> He was the plenary speaker at a conference on transcultural issues in child psychiatry, at McGill University a pioneering research center in [[transcultural psychiatry]], the proceedings of which were published (Sayegh, ''et al.'', 1992).<ref>{{Cite book |veditors=Sayegh L, Migenault P, Grizenko N |title=Transcultural Issues in Child Psychiatry |year=1992 |place=Montreal, QC |publisher=\u00c9dition Douglas |isbn=978-2-98009-632-7 |oclc=497660765 }}</ref>\n\nDi Nicola's work on eating disorders called for a new historical and cultural view of what he called \"anorexia multiforme,\" a form of suffering that is a cultural chameleon, expressing itself differently in different times, cultures and places.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/136346159002700301 |title=Anorexia Multiforme: Self-starvation in Historical and Cultural Context Part I: Self-starvation as a Historical Chameleon1 |year=1990 |last1=DiNicola |first1=V. F. |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |volume=27 |issue=3 |page=165}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/136346159002700401 |title=Anorexia Multiforme: Self-Starvation in Historical and Cultural Context: Part II: Anorexia Nervosa as a Culture-Reactive Syndrome1 |year=1990 |last1=DiNicola |first1=V. F. |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |volume=27 |issue=4 |page=245}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Eating-Disorders-and-Cultures-in-Transition/Nasser-Katzman-Gordon/p/book/9780203361245|title=Changing bodies, changing cultures: An intercultural dialogue on the body as the final frontier. In: Eating Disorders and Cultures in Transition|last=Nasser|first=Mervat|last2=Di Nicola|first2=Vincenzo|date=2004|year=2004|editor-last=Nasser|editor-first=Mervat|website=www.routledge.com|publisher=Routledge|location=East Sussex, UK|pages=171-193|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://valuesbasedpractice.org/anorexia-multiforme-revisited/|title=Anorexia Multiforme Revisited|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2019-10-15|website=The Collaborating Centre for Values-based practice in Health and Social Care|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nA major area of Di Nicola's academic activity is in [[Social psychiatry]], focused on the [[social determinants of health]] and mental health,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jblearning.com/catalog/productdetails/9781449627874#productInfo|title=21st Century Global Mental Health|website=www.jblearning.com|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> his manifesto for social psychiatry, outlining the history, current state and future prospects of Social psychiatry,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2019-01-01|title=\"A person is a person through other persons\": A social psychiatry manifesto for the 21st century|url=http://www.worldsocpsychiatry.org/article.asp?issn=WKMP-0196;year=2019;volume=1;issue=1;spage=8;epage=21;aulast=Di|journal=World Social Psychiatry|language=en|volume=1|issue=1|pages=8\u201321|doi=10.4103/WSP.WSP_11_19|doi-broken-date=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.madinamerica.com/2019/10/social-psychiatry-manifesto-takes-social-context-seriously/|title=A Social Psychiatry Manifesto that Takes Social Context Seriously|last=Ingle|first=Micah|date=2019-10-17|website=Mad In America|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> and his essay on the sociopolitical notion of the [[Global South]] as a bridge between [[globalization]] and the [[global mental health]] (GMH) movement that offers an emergent apparatus or conceptual tool for social psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2020-01-01|title=The Global South: An emergent epistemology for social psychiatry|url=http://www.worldsocpsychiatry.org/article.asp?issn=WKMP-0196;year=2020;volume=2;issue=1;spage=20;epage=26;aulast=Di;type=0|journal=World Social Psychiatry|language=en|volume=2|issue=1|pages=20-26|doi=10.4103/WSP.WSP_1_20|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== '''Interface between Philosophy and Psychiatry''' ====\nDi Nicola's work also focuses on the interface between [[philosophy]] and psychiatry, addressing philosophical issues ranging from the rights of children, to employing [[Giorgio Agamben]]'s \"state of exception\" in definitions of human being and in trauma studies, and [[Alain Badiou]]'s \"event\" in his work on Trauma and Event, announcing a Psychiatry of the Event and a manifesto for Slow Thought in the spirit of the [[Slow movement (culture)|Slow Movement]]:\n\n* \"Review-essay: On the rights and philosophy of children\"<ref>{{cite journal |author=Vincenzo Di Nicola |title=Review-essay: On the rights and philosophy of children |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |year=1995 |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=157\u2013165 |doi=10.1177/136346159503200203}}</ref> \n* \"States of exception, states of dissociation: Cyranoids, zombies and liminal people - An essay on the threshold between the human and the inhuman\"<ref>{{cite journal |author=Vincenzo Di Nicola |title=States of exception, states of dissociation: Cyranoids, zombies and liminal people - An essay on the threshold between the human and the inhuman |journal=Journal of the International Association of Transdisciplinary Psychology |date= May 2010 |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201314 |url=http://www.transdisciplinarypsych.org/Final_DiNicola.pdf |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728124053/http://www.transdisciplinarypsych.org/Final_DiNicola.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-28}}</ref> \n* \"Where the exception becomes the norm \u2014 At the juncture of culture, trauma and psychiatry: Applying Agamben\u2019s 'state of exception' to trauma studies and cultural competence\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/tcpsych/sites/mcgill.ca.../sspc_2010_program.pdf|title=Where the exception becomes the norm \u2014 At the juncture of culture, trauma and psychiatry: Applying Agamben's \"state of exception\" to trauma studies and cultural competence|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=1 May 2010|website=www.mcgill.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n*\"Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 1: Trauma and Event\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/11/23/badiou-the-event-and-psychiatry-part-1-trauma-and-event/|title=Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 1: Trauma and Event|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=23 November 2017|website=Blog of the APA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n*\"Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 2: Psychiatry of the Event\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/11/30/badiou-the-event-and-psychiatry-part-2-psychiatry-of-the-event/|title=Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 2: Psychiatry of the Event|last=Contributor|first=Blog|date=2017-11-30|website=Blog of the APA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n*\"Two Trauma Communities: A Philosophical Archaeology of Cultural and Clinical Trauma Theories\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fordhampress.com/9780823280261/trauma-and-transcendence|title=Trauma and Transcendence|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Fordham University Press|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n*\"Take Your Time: The Seven Pillars of a Slow Thought Manifesto\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aeon.co/essays/take-your-time-the-seven-pillars-of-a-slow-thought-manifesto|title=Take your time: the seven pillars of a Slow Thought manifesto \u2013 Vincenzo Di Nicola {{!}} Aeon Essays|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Aeon|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://getpocket.com/explore/item/slow-thought-a-manifesto|title=Slow Thought: A Manifesto|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Pocket|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/apres-le-slow-food-voici-le-slow-thoughts-96189|title=Apr\u00e8s le \" slow food \", voici le \" slow thoughts \"|last=Gendreau|first=Sylvie|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> See: \"Thought (Philosophy)\" section in: [[Slow movement (culture)]]\n\n===Books===\n* ''The Myth of Atlas: Families and the Therapeutic Story'' (Editor and translator; Routledge, 1989), {{ISBN|0876305494}}\n* ''Families That Abuse'' (Foreword; W.W. Norton, 1992), {{ISBN|0393701220}}\n* ''[[A Stranger in the Family]]: Culture, Families, and Therapy'' (W.W. Norton, 1997), {{ISBN|0393702286}} \n*''Um Estranho na Fam\u00edlia: Cultura, Fam\u00edlias e Terapia'' (Artmed, 1998, trans. by Maria Adriana Ver\u00edssimo Veronese), {{ISBN|9788573074642}}\n* ''Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community'' (Atropos, 2011), {{ISBN|0983173451}}\n* ''The Unsecured Present'' (Atropos, 2012), {{ISBN|978-0-9853042-7-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Nicola, Vincenzo}}\n[[Category:Canadian psychiatrists]]\n[[Category:Canadian psychologists]]\n[[Category:Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Vincenzo Di Nicola APA Photo Nov 2017b.jpg|thumb|Prof. Vincenzo Di Nicola, MPhil, MD, PhD, FRCPC, DFAPA]]\n'''Vincenzo Di Nicola''' is an [[Italian Canadians|Italian-Canadian]] [[psychologist]], [[psychiatrist]] and [[family therapist]], and [[Philosophy of mind|philosopher of mind]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwumc.edu/smhs/facultydirectory/profile.cfm?empName=Vincenzo%20Di%20Nicola&FacID=2066720133#|title=Faculty Directory {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences {{!}} The George Washington University|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=www.gwumc.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> \n\nDi Nicola is a tenured Professor in the Dept. of Psychiatry & Addictions at the [[University of Montreal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etudes.umontreal.ca/publications/annu_pdf/2011-2012/1erCycle/MED_tap.pdf|title=Faculte de Medicine|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2011\u20132012|website=|publisher=University of Montreal|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> where he founded and directs the postgraduate course on Psychiatry and the Humanities,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/03/23/psychiatry-and-the-humanities-postgraduate-course-in-the-faculty-of-medicine-university-of-montreal/|title=Psychiatry and the Humanities: Postgraduate Course in the Faculty of Medicine, University of Montreal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2017-03-23|website=Blog of the APA|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> and Clinical Professor in the Dept. of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at [[The George Washington University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwumc.edu/smhs/facultydirectory/profile.cfm?empName=Vincenzo%20Di%20Nicola&FacID=2066720133#|title=Faculty Directory {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences {{!}} The George Washington University|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=www.gwumc.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> where he gave The 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smhs.gwu.edu/psychiatry/events/grand-rounds-4th-annual-stokes-endowment-lecture|title=Grand Rounds: The 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture {{!}} The Department of Psychiatry & Behavioral Sciences|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=smhs.gwu.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> In 2001, Di Nicola was made Professor, Honoris Causa of [[:pt:Faculdades_Integradas_do_Oeste_de_Minas|Faculdades Integradas do Oeste de Minas (FADOM)]] in Minas Gerais, Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://recherche.umontreal.ca/english/our-researchers/professors-directory/researcher/is/in17672/|title=Researcher|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=La recherche - Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>   \n\nDi Nicola was the recipient of the Camille Laurin Prize from the F\u00e9d\u00e9ration des m\u00e9decins sp\u00e9cialistes du Qu\u00e9bec.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration des m\u00e9decins sp\u00e9cialistes du Qu\u00e9bec |date=June 4, 2011 |url=http://www.fmsq.org/en/nouvelle/-/journal_content/contentdisplayerportlet_WAR_contentdisplayer10/10275/52216;jsessionid=8AA0EFBC8F03956910634FBD9C2DF83F?p_p_state=pop_up&_contentdisplayerportlet_WAR_contentdisplayer10_viewMode=print |title=AMPQ Annual Prizes |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> He was made a Fellow of the [[American Psychiatric Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psych.org/MainMenu/EducationCareerDevelopment/Meetings/Past-APA-Meetings/2011-Annual-Meeting/Virtual-Registration-Bag_1/Onsite-Meeting-Guides/Convocation-Program.aspx?FT=.pdf|title=55th convocation of distinguished fellows|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=May 16, 2011|website=|publisher=The American Psychiatric Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 2, 2012}}</ref> (APA) in 2011 and Distinguished Fellow of the APA in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://recherche.umontreal.ca/english/our-researchers/professors-directory/researcher/is/in17672/|title=Researcher, Dept of Psychiatry|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=La recherche - Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> In 2018, the [[American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry]] (AACAP) awarded Di Nicola the AACAP Jeanne Spurlock, MD, Lecture and Award on Diversity and Culture<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aacap.org/App_Themes/AACAP/docs/awards/aacap_honors_book_2018.pdf|title=AACAP Honors 2018|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=25 October 2018|website=www.aacap.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> for which he gave the lecture, \u201cBorders and Belonging, Culture and Community: From Adversity to Diversity in Transcultural Child and Family Psychiatry.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2018-10-01|title=Borders and Belonging, Culture and Community: From Adversity to Diversity in Transcultural Child and Family Psychiatry|url=https://www.jaacap.org/article/S0890-8567(18)31360-1/abstract|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry|language=English|volume=57|issue=10|pages=S116|doi=10.1016/j.jaac.2018.09.013|issn=0890-8567|via=}}</ref>  \n\nDi Nicola is a collaborating partner of the Collaborating Centre for Values-based Practice in Health and Social Care at St. Catherine's College, Oxford University<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://valuesbasedpractice.org/who-are-we-2/list-of-project-partners/list-of-individuals/professor-vincenzo-di-nicola/|title=Professor Vincenzo Di Nicola|date=2019-11-08|website=The Collaborating Centre for Values-based practice in Health and Social Care|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> where he participated in the Advanced Studies Seminar dedicated to his work on cultural aspects of eating disorders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://valuesbasedpractice.org/anorexia-multiforme-revisited/|title=Anorexia Multiforme Revisited|date=2019-10-15|website=The Collaborating Centre for Values-based practice in Health and Social Care|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> In 2019, he founded and was elected President of the Canadian Association of Social Psychiatry<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/associations/|title=ASSOCIATIONS {{!}} WASP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> and was made an Honorary Fellow of the [https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/ World Association of Social Psychiatry],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/wasp-honorary-fellows/|title=WASP Honorary Fellows {{!}} WASP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> of which he is President-Elect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waspsocialpsychiatry.org/wasp-executive-committee/|title=WASP Executive Committee {{!}} WASP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nDi Nicola is the author of two books, ''[[A Stranger in the Family]]: Culture, Families, and Therapy'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwnorton.com/books/9780393702286|title=A Stranger in the Family: Culture, Families, and Therapy|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=wwnorton.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> integrating family therapy and cultural psychiatry to create cultural family therapy, and ''Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atropospress.com/letters-to-a-young-therapist-relational-practices-for-the-coming-community|title=Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Atropos Press|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> an overview of principles of relational psychology and therapy.\n\n==Education==\nDi Nicola trained in psychology, medicine and psychiatry, and in philosophy: with a BA (First Class Honours) in Psychology from [[McGill University]] (1976), MPhil in Clinical Psychology, [[Institute of Psychiatry, Psychology and Neuroscience|Institute of Psychiatry]], University of London (1978), [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] from [[McMaster University]] (1981), Diploma in Psychiatry from McGill University (1986), and later in his career, with a PhD (Summa Cum Laude) in Philosophy from the [[European Graduate School|European Graduate Schoo]]<nowiki/>l (2012).<ref name=Alumnotes>{{cite web |publisher=McGill University, McGill News, Alumni magazine |date=Spring\u2013Summer 2011 |url=http://publications.mcgill.ca/mcgillnews/2011/06/02/alumnotes-springsummer-2011/ |title=Alumnotes Spring/Summer2011 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611112929/http://publications.mcgill.ca/mcgillnews/2011/06/02/alumnotes-springsummer-2011/ |archive-date=June 11, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Mactimes>{{cite web |publisher=McMaster University |date=Spring 2011 |url=http://issuu.com/mactimes/docs/times_april_2011_-_updated |title=Mactimes/Spring2011 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwumc.edu/smhs/facultydirectory/profile.cfm?empName=Vincenzo%20Di%20Nicola&FacID=2066720133|title=Faculty Directory {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences {{!}} The George Washington University|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=www.gwumc.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nDi Nicola's career has shown several foci, examining children, families and culture in various combinations.<ref name=\"Doi\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/136346158502200201 |title=Family Therapy and Transcultural Psychiatry: An Emerging Synthesis Part I: The Conceptual Basis |year=1985 |last1=DiNicola |first1=V. F. |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |volume=22 |issue=2 |page=81}}</ref><ref name=\"Isbn\">{{cite book |title=A stranger in the family: culture, families and therapy |first=Vincenzo F |last=DiNicola |location=New York ; London |publisher=W.W. Norton |date=1997 |isbn=978-0-39370-228-6}}</ref><ref name=\"InOkpaku\">{{Cite book |editor-last=Okpaku |editor-first=Sanuel O. |title=Clinical Methods in Transcultural Psychiatry |journal=Cultural Diversity & Ethnic Minority Psychology |volume=8 |issue=3 |year=1998 |place=Washington, DC |publisher=American Psychiatric Association |pages=365\u2013390 |doi=10.1037/1099-9809.8.3.298 |isbn=978-0-88048-710-8}}</ref>\n\n==== '''Cultural Family Therapy''' ====\n''Main article:'' [[A Stranger in the Family|''A Stranger in the Family'']]\n\nHis approach to working with families across cultures brought together a new synthesis of family therapy and transcultural psychiatry.<ref name=\"Doi\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=DiNicola|first=Vincenzo F.|date=1985|title=Family Therapy and Transcultural Psychiatry: An Emerging Synthesis|journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review|language=en-US|volume=22|issue=3|pages=151\u2013180|doi=10.1177/136346158502200301|issn=0041-1108}}</ref> Critical reviews were positive and encouraging by leaders in family therapy, such as [[Mara Selvini Palazzoli]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Selvini Palazzoli|first=Mara|date=1986|title=COMMENTS ON DI NICOLA'S \"FAMILY THERAPY AND TRANSCULTURAL PSYCHIATRY: PARTS 1 AND 2 (Published in T.P.R.R. Volume XXII, Nos. 2 and 3, pp. 81-113 and 151-180). LETTER FROM MARA SELVINI PALAZZOLI, M.D., Nuovo Centro Per Lo Studio Della Famiglia, Viale Vitorio Veneto, 12, Milano 21124, Italy|journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review|language=en|volume=23|issue=1|pages=83\u201385|doi=10.1177/136346158602300114}}</ref> and Celia Jaes Falicov,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/sage/comments-on-di-nicola-s-family-therapy-and-transcultural-psychiatry-QTrL8CpL6c |title=Comments on DI NICOLA'S Family Therapy and Transcultural Psychiatry: Parts 1 and 2 (TPRR, XXII, Nos. 2 and 3, pp. 81-113 and 151-180) |author=Celia Jaes Falicov |journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review |volume=23 |issue=2 |page=5 |date=Jun 1, 1986 |via=DeepDyve |accessdate=2013-02-23}}</ref> as well as those in transcultural psychiatry, such as [[Armando Favazza]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Favazza|first=Armando R.|date=1 March 1986|title=LETTER FROM ARMANDO R. FAVAZZA, M.D., Section of General Psychiatry, Department of Psychiatry, School of Medicine, Uni versity of Missouri-Columbia, Three Hospital Drive, Columbia, Missouri 65201, U.S.A|journal=Transcultural Psychiatric Research Review|language=en-US|volume=23|issue=1|pages=86\u201391|doi=10.1177/136346158602300115|issn=0041-1108}}</ref> When his work was collected into his model of cultural family therapy in ''[[A Stranger in the Family]]''<ref name=\"Isbn\" /> in 1997, it was received as an important contribution to working with immigrant families.<ref>{{cite journal |volume=187 |pages=453\u2013454 |journal=Journal of Nervous & Mental Disease |date=July 1999 |title=A Stranger in The Family: Culture, Families, and Therapy |author=Comas-D\u00edaz, Lillian |issue=7 |doi=10.1097/00005053-199907000-00016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Krause, Inga-Britt|date=Dec 1, 1998|title=Book Reviews : A STRANGER IN THE FAMILY. CULTURE, FAMILIES AND THERAPY Vincenzo Di Nicola: W.W. Norton & Co. New York, 1997. Pp. 380, Hb. Bibl; index 33.00. ISBN 0-393-70228-6|url=http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/sage/book-reviews-a-stranger-in-the-family-culture-families-and-therapy-T9ipODhRDl|journal=International Journal of Social Psychiatry|volume=44|issue=4|page=312|doi=10.1177/002076409804400409|accessdate=2012-04-09|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |volume=20 |page=174 |journal=Australian and New Zealand Journal of Family Therapy |year=1999 |url=http://www.anzjft.com/pages/articles/1103.pdf |author=Sexton, Leo |title=REVIEWS: Independent comment on audio-visual and print materials |accessdate=2012-04-09 |issue=3 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318061824/http://www.anzjft.com/pages/articles/1103.pdf |archive-date=2012-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bezonsky-Jacobs|first=Rhona|date=1999|title=Review of 'A Stranger in the Family: Culture, Families, and Therapy'|journal=PRISME|volume=No. 30|pages=156\u2013158|isbn=0393702286}}</ref> A Brazilian edition in Portuguese translation appeared in 1998.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|title=Um Estranho na Fam\u00edlia: Cultura, Fam\u00edlias e Terapia|date=1998|publisher=Artmed|year=1998|isbn=85-7307-464-7|location=Porto Alegre|pages=|oclc=69926813}}</ref> Di Nicola continued to elaborate his model of cultural family therapy in articles, chapters,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibs.it/famiglie-immigrate-psicoterapia-transculturale-libro-vari/e/9788846456397|title=Famiglie sulla soglia. Citt\u00e0 invisibili, identit\u00e0 invisibili. In: Famiglie immigrate e psicoterapia transculturale|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2012|year=2012|editor-last=Andolfi|editor-first=Maurizio|website=www.ibs.it|publisher=FrancoAngeli|pages=34-57|language=Italian|trans-title=Families on the threshold: Invisible cities, invisible identities. In: Immigrant Families and Transcultural Psychotherapy|publication-place=Milan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a follow-up volume, ''Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/703204731|title=Letters to a Young Therapist Relational Practices for the Coming Community|date=2011|publisher=Atropos Books|others=|year=2011|isbn=978-0-9831734-5-8|location=New York and Dresden|pages=|oclc=703204731}}</ref> as well as invitations to present the 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture in family studies at [[George Washington University|The George Washington University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smhs.gwu.edu/psychiatry/events/grand-rounds-4th-annual-stokes-endowment-lecture|title=Grand Rounds: The 4th Annual Stokes Endowment Lecture {{!}} The Department of Psychiatry & Behavioral Sciences|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=April 25, 2013|website=smhs.gwu.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and a thirty-year perspective on his model presented at [[McGill University]] where he first developed it <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/psychiatry/channels/event/grand-rounds-threshold-event-thirty-years-cultural-family-therapy-dr-vincenzo-di-nicola-259678|title=Grand Rounds: From the Threshold to the Event: Thirty Years of Cultural Family Therapy - Dr. Vincenzo Di Nicola|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=March 18, 2016|website=Department of Psychiatry, McGill University|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and the Accademia di Psicoterapia della [http://www.accademiapsico.it/ Famiglia] in Rome, Italy where Di Nicola's model is taught.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slideshare.net/PhiloShrink/dalla-soglia-allevento-lo-svolgimento-della-terapia-familiare-culturale|title=Dalla Soglia all'Evento: Lo Svolgimento della Terapia Familiare Culturale. Giornata di Lezioni Teoriche - Accademia di Psicoterapia della Famiglia, Roma, Italia|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=April 9, 2016|website=www.slideshare.net/PhiloShrink|language=Italian|trans-title=From the Threshold to the Event: The Development of Cultural Family Therapy. Academic Teaching Day - Academy of Family Psychotherapy, Rome, Italy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== '''Social and Cultural Psychiatry''' ====\nAnother integration was in bringing together child psychiatry with transcultural research to call for the new field of transcultural child psychiatry.<ref name=\"InOkpaku\" /> He was the plenary speaker at a conference on transcultural issues in child psychiatry, at McGill University a pioneering research center in [[transcultural psychiatry]], the proceedings of which were published (Sayegh, ''et al.'', 1992).<ref>{{Cite book |veditors=Sayegh L, Migenault P, Grizenko N |title=Transcultural Issues in Child Psychiatry |year=1992 |place=Montreal, QC |publisher=\u00c9dition Douglas |isbn=978-2-98009-632-7 |oclc=497660765 }}</ref>\n\nDi Nicola's work on eating disorders called for a new historical and cultural view of what he called \"anorexia multiforme,\" a form of suffering that is a cultural chameleon, expressing itself differently in different times, cultures and places.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/136346159002700301 |title=Anorexia Multiforme: Self-starvation in Historical and Cultural Context Part I: Self-starvation as a Historical Chameleon1 |year=1990 |last1=DiNicola |first1=V. F. |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |volume=27 |issue=3 |page=165}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/136346159002700401 |title=Anorexia Multiforme: Self-Starvation in Historical and Cultural Context: Part II: Anorexia Nervosa as a Culture-Reactive Syndrome1 |year=1990 |last1=DiNicola |first1=V. F. |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |volume=27 |issue=4 |page=245}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Eating-Disorders-and-Cultures-in-Transition/Nasser-Katzman-Gordon/p/book/9780203361245|title=Changing bodies, changing cultures: An intercultural dialogue on the body as the final frontier. In: Eating Disorders and Cultures in Transition|last=Nasser|first=Mervat|last2=Di Nicola|first2=Vincenzo|date=2004|year=2004|editor-last=Nasser|editor-first=Mervat|website=www.routledge.com|publisher=Routledge|location=East Sussex, UK|pages=171-193|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://valuesbasedpractice.org/anorexia-multiforme-revisited/|title=Anorexia Multiforme Revisited|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2019-10-15|website=The Collaborating Centre for Values-based practice in Health and Social Care|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nA major area of Di Nicola's academic activity is in [[Social psychiatry]], focused on the [[social determinants of health]] and mental health,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jblearning.com/catalog/productdetails/9781449627874#productInfo|title=21st Century Global Mental Health|website=www.jblearning.com|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> his manifesto for social psychiatry, outlining the history, current state and future prospects of Social psychiatry,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2019-01-01|title=\"A person is a person through other persons\": A social psychiatry manifesto for the 21st century|url=http://www.worldsocpsychiatry.org/article.asp?issn=WKMP-0196;year=2019;volume=1;issue=1;spage=8;epage=21;aulast=Di|journal=World Social Psychiatry|language=en|volume=1|issue=1|pages=8\u201321|doi=10.4103/WSP.WSP_11_19|doi-broken-date=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.madinamerica.com/2019/10/social-psychiatry-manifesto-takes-social-context-seriously/|title=A Social Psychiatry Manifesto that Takes Social Context Seriously|last=MA|first=Micah Ingle|date=2019-10-17|website=Mad In America|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> and his essay on the sociopolitical notion of the [[Global South]] as a bridge between [[globalization]] and the [[global mental health]] (GMH) movement that offers an emergent apparatus or conceptual tool for social psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=2020-01-01|title=The Global South: An emergent epistemology for social psychiatry|url=http://www.worldsocpsychiatry.org/article.asp?issn=WKMP-0196;year=2020;volume=2;issue=1;spage=20;epage=26;aulast=Di;type=0|journal=World Social Psychiatry|language=en|volume=2|issue=1|pages=20-26|doi=10.4103/WSP.WSP_1_20|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== '''Interface between Philosophy and Psychiatry''' ====\nDi Nicola's work also focuses on the interface between [[philosophy]] and psychiatry, addressing philosophical issues ranging from the rights of children, to employing [[Giorgio Agamben]]'s \"state of exception\" in definitions of human being and in trauma studies, and [[Alain Badiou]]'s \"event\" in his work on Trauma and Event, announcing a Psychiatry of the Event and a manifesto for Slow Thought in the spirit of the [[Slow movement (culture)|Slow Movement]]:\n\n* \"Review-essay: On the rights and philosophy of children\"<ref>{{cite journal |author=Vincenzo Di Nicola |title=Review-essay: On the rights and philosophy of children |journal=Transcultural Psychiatry |year=1995 |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=157\u2013165 |doi=10.1177/136346159503200203}}</ref> \n* \"States of exception, states of dissociation: Cyranoids, zombies and liminal people - An essay on the threshold between the human and the inhuman\"<ref>{{cite journal |author=Vincenzo Di Nicola |title=States of exception, states of dissociation: Cyranoids, zombies and liminal people - An essay on the threshold between the human and the inhuman |journal=Journal of the International Association of Transdisciplinary Psychology |date= May 2010 |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201314 |url=http://www.transdisciplinarypsych.org/Final_DiNicola.pdf |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728124053/http://www.transdisciplinarypsych.org/Final_DiNicola.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-28}}</ref> \n* \"Where the exception becomes the norm \u2014 At the juncture of culture, trauma and psychiatry: Applying Agamben\u2019s 'state of exception' to trauma studies and cultural competence\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/tcpsych/sites/mcgill.ca.../sspc_2010_program.pdf|title=Where the exception becomes the norm \u2014 At the juncture of culture, trauma and psychiatry: Applying Agamben's \"state of exception\" to trauma studies and cultural competence|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=1 May 2010|website=www.mcgill.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n*\"Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 1: Trauma and Event\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/11/23/badiou-the-event-and-psychiatry-part-1-trauma-and-event/|title=Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 1: Trauma and Event|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=23 November 2017|website=Blog of the APA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n*\"Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 2: Psychiatry of the Event\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/11/30/badiou-the-event-and-psychiatry-part-2-psychiatry-of-the-event/|title=Badiou, the Event, and Psychiatry, Part 2: Psychiatry of the Event|last=Contributor|first=Blog|date=2017-11-30|website=Blog of the APA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n*\"Two Trauma Communities: A Philosophical Archaeology of Cultural and Clinical Trauma Theories\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fordhampress.com/9780823280261/trauma-and-transcendence|title=Trauma and Transcendence|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Fordham University Press|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n*\"Take Your Time: The Seven Pillars of a Slow Thought Manifesto\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aeon.co/essays/take-your-time-the-seven-pillars-of-a-slow-thought-manifesto|title=Take your time: the seven pillars of a Slow Thought manifesto \u2013 Vincenzo Di Nicola {{!}} Aeon Essays|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Aeon|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://getpocket.com/explore/item/slow-thought-a-manifesto|title=Slow Thought: A Manifesto|last=Di Nicola|first=Vincenzo|date=|website=Pocket|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/apres-le-slow-food-voici-le-slow-thoughts-96189|title=Apr\u00e8s le \" slow food \", voici le \" slow thoughts \"|last=Gendreau|first=Sylvie|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> See: \"Thought (Philosophy)\" section in: [[Slow movement (culture)]]\n\n===Books===\n* ''The Myth of Atlas: Families and the Therapeutic Story'' (Editor and translator; Routledge, 1989), {{ISBN|0876305494}}\n* ''Families That Abuse'' (Foreword; W.W. Norton, 1992), {{ISBN|0393701220}}\n* ''[[A Stranger in the Family]]: Culture, Families, and Therapy'' (W.W. Norton, 1997), {{ISBN|0393702286}} \n*''Um Estranho na Fam\u00edlia: Cultura, Fam\u00edlias e Terapia'' (Artmed, 1998, trans. by Maria Adriana Ver\u00edssimo Veronese), {{ISBN|9788573074642}}\n* ''Letters to a Young Therapist: Relational Practices for the Coming Community'' (Atropos, 2011), {{ISBN|0983173451}}\n* ''The Unsecured Present'' (Atropos, 2012), {{ISBN|978-0-9853042-7-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Nicola, Vincenzo}}\n[[Category:Canadian psychiatrists]]\n[[Category:Canadian psychologists]]\n[[Category:Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Frederico L", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correction of reference to review of Slow thought manifesto by Micah Ingle in Mad in America (name was mixed up with his degree)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vincenzo_Di_Nicola"}
